{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Sd7UGXc4Z2BYfFqDxaSwZP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Both are Ray 2.9.0. The issue seems to be that when `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` is called in the client pod, it tries to connect as a regular worker node, not as a Ray client. This requires the local raylet to be set up.\n\nThe error is `Can't find a node_ip_address.json file` which means it tried to start a raylet locally (inside the client container) and couldn't.\n\nThis is the classic problem with `ray.init(address='...')` - it tries to connect as a full worker node, which requires the raylet binary and some local initialization. \n\nIn a plain Python pod without a running raylet, the fix would be to use the Ray Client protocol instead with `ray.init(\"ray://ray-head:10001\")` on port 10001. But the validation command is hardcoded to use the GCS address on port 6379, and with Ray 2.9.0, that approach attempts to set up a full worker connection locally, which fails without the necessary raylet infrastructure.\n\nThe `node_ip_address.json` file only gets created when `ray start` runs on a node, so the `ray-client` pod never creates it since no local raylet was started. Looking at the error sequence, it successfully connects to the GCS first, then fails when trying to initialize the local raylet—this is the expected behavior in Ray 2.9.0 when using `ray.init(address='...')` without having first run `ray start --address=...` locally.\n\nThe solution is either to start a local raylet in the pod before calling `ray.init()`, or switch to using the Ray Client protocol with `ray://ray-head:10001` instead. I could use the Ray Client protocol with `ray://<head>:<client_port>` instead, but the validation command specifically uses `ray-head:6379`, so I need to make that work. The real issue is that when `ray.init(address=...)` is called without a local raylet already running, it needs to start one, and that's where things break down in the container environment.\n\nLooking at the actual error, Ray is trying to find a `node_ip_address.json` file in the session directory but can't locate it—this file only gets created when `ray start` is run locally, which isn't happening in the validation container. different version of Ray than the head node, or there's a mismatch in how the client is trying to connect. Let me think about what the actual fix should be without modifying the ray-client pod itself. So the validation command needs to output \"ok\" as the expected result. I could try running `ray start --address=ray-head:6379` inside the ray-client pod first to set it up as a worker node, then execute the Python validation command—this should work without modifying the pod spec itself.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":627,"cache_read_input_tokens":32338,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":627},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"aa44d4b7-b67c-4b1e-9b3b-e6e6a247b2cb","uuid":"60be3b8d-7f47-4115-b6b4-0121589759d4","request_id":"req_011CccMoQrQSTU99CkfKJEx1"}
